<section id="abstract" class="paper-col py-10">
  <p class="section-num">Abstract</p>
  <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-6">
    <p class="mb-4">
      When a card BIN is dual&#8209;branded (e.g.&nbsp;Visa and Cartes Bancaires on a French issuer), the
      acquiring bank must choose <em>which</em> scheme receives the authorization request. The
      decision is a multi&#8209;objective problem: maximize the expected authorization rate while
      minimizing the interchange cost &mdash; objectives that frequently conflict and whose ideal
      trade&#8209;off varies with transaction context (amount, cross&#8209;border, MCC risk profile).
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      We present an end&#8209;to&#8209;end serverless prototype in which an LLM agent (AWS Bedrock,
      Claude Sonnet&nbsp;4.6) executes a ReAct (<em>Reason + Act</em>) tool&#8209;use loop over four
      domain tools backed by DynamoDB and an in&#8209;Lambda XGBoost&#8209;to&#8209;ONNX regression
      model. The agent emits a structured, explainable decision &mdash; selected scheme,
      confidence, ranked fallback chain, and per&#8209;scheme score breakdown &mdash; using adaptive
      weights that shift toward authorization rate for high&#8209;risk transactions.
    </p>
    <p>
      The interchange model achieves <strong>MAE&nbsp;0.039&thinsp;%</strong>,
      <strong>RMSE&nbsp;0.054&thinsp;%</strong>, and <strong>R&sup2;&nbsp;0.9988</strong> on a
      held&#8209;out split of 25,000 synthetic settlement records. The system is deployed to AWS
      via SAM (Lambda + API&nbsp;Gateway + DynamoDB + S3) and reproduces three published demo
      scenarios with explainable rationales.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
